column49: The materials provided and your instruction allowed to class to quickly get to work as they began to solve the problem you provided. The was no misuse of time and it looked as if everyone was clear on the steps needed to justify their answer.
column53: From what I have observed in person and in your video, your students are enjoying the class and you as their teacher. This I attribute to the tools you have set in place, your love for Math, teaching and your students. When they know you care it is that much easier to get them to work and try things th
column57: When you asked the class to turn and talk they did, when you directed them to begin looking at the problem and predicting which gift they thought was the best, they did. Your class is engaged and responsive due to your giving them the techniques they need to get started.
column59: Your written reflection of your video was spot on. Your lesson was excellent and well executed and it appears your class is moving in a positive direction. You are consistent	so the class follows your instruction easily. I did not see the error you pointed out in your reflection as it happened when you were talking to a student one on one but I appreciate your pointing it out. It is important to correct ourselves to our class. They need to know we also make errors and that it is ok to point out an error and then to correct it.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79 Safari/537.36 Edge/14.14393
column49: This was an excellent class where students were actively involved in the learning process throughout and ended with each student accessing their involvement in the lesson.  Instructional outcomes were clearly stated, assessments threaded throughout the activities and students were able to work at their own pace. The stations set up throughout the class helped the students to break down the problem ensuring they did not miss a step. This also allowed each student to see which station (part of the problem) gave them the most trouble and the area they needed to work on.
column53: The class worked continuously throughout the lesson with only one student needing prompting (in the form of one on one instruction). We did speak at length about this situation as well as to the IEP coordinator who discussed the strategies the school has been trying to implement for this student. Aside from this student (who was certainly pleasant) the rest of the class actively enjoyed the lesson. Math can be scary to some students, but that did not seem to be happening in your class. 2c. Managing classroom procedures = 5 The class ran from beginning to end like a well-oiled machine. You were able to hit all your objectives from your Do Now to your Exit Ticket today. 2d. Managing student behavior = 5 There were very few behavior issues today which were quickly put to rest and did not interrupt the class for a second. One student came in late and as soon as you could you handed her the late book without reminding her what she needed to do. She wrote a paragraph on why she was late. Another student (the one I described earlier who needed one on one help) was playing on his tablet which you quietly walked over to him motioning for him to put it away, which he did.
column57: Your questions were good but they tended not to lead to discussions. After a mini lesson where students were called on to read, the questions asked were for the formula needed and if the example you were looking at showed growth or decay.  3c. Engaging students in learning = 5 The timing of the activities and the pace of the students moving through the activities was excellent. The students had 4 questions they needed to answer while moving around the stations. One student was able to complete all 4, while most of the class was about to complete 3 as the 4th question was a bit of a trick understanding what they needed to do. 3d. Using assessment in instruction = 5 Assessment was threaded throughout the lesson ending with the exit ticket giving the students a chance to self-assess where they were in the learning process. This gave the class an opportunity to look at their strengths and weaknesses which allowed them to reflect of themselves as learners.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79 Safari/537.36 Edge/14.14393
column49: You lesson is set up with good expectations but the class fights you in implementing it.
column53: 2b. Establishing a culture for learning = 2 You are working very hard from beginning to the end of your lesson but your class shows little commitment or desire to do little more than the bare minimum of what is expected of them. This is the culture of the class with the students leading this, not you the teacher! 2c. Managing classroom procedures = 2 2d. Managing student behavior = 2 Try not to pull class together until you are ready to work with them. Too much time is wasted by trying to get their attention then not keeping it. When you are ready to do your lesson, most do quiet down and listen. For those who continue to make noise, I suggest you walk over and stand near them and if that doesn't work, gently touch a shoulder. This often has the desired effect of quieting them down. Move around the room, do not stand in front for the entire class. By moving around you keep the class off balance. After you give directions students ask again and again what to do. Ask them to think for a second and try to remember what you said. They need to do more work and not constantly rely on you for personalized instruction. They are not asking because you are not being clear, they are asking because they didn't listen while you were talking.
column57: You need to plan this class from bell to bell and not give them a minute to breathe. This will make it easier on both you and them. I suggest you show the class the video as it does not reflect behavior they would be proud of and they need to see this. I am still seeing one word answers and no discussion among the classmates. The general mode of thinking in this class is this is just a chill period and they only have to do the littlest work to get by.  I like the way you call out students who are doing what is expected of them. It has not yet had the desired effect of making the rest of the class follow but with consistency in your actions, they will begin to pull together.
column59: I think you did a very good job reflecting on your video lesson and your teaching of the lesson. You would have much more time to complete all the activities in your lesson if you began class at the bell and did not spend so much time pulling the class together. You can have your para give out the Regents papers or whatever papers are given to you to hand out to the class. Use the timer on your computer which can be reflected onto your smart board so the class can see how much time they have left for each activity.

column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79 Safari/537.36 Edge/14.14393
column49: This was the first time I saw your 11th grade US History class and it was a pleasure to see the maturity in the student's responses. You know your material and have solid instructional outcomes which was evident in the way you lead the class through the discussions.
column53: All behavior was on target. Students know what to expect in your class and no time is wasted in getting them started. In your reflection you answered this question beautify: "the best classroom management is a good engaging lesson"  Your questions are clear and are often the stimulus needed for a discussion. You never accept a one word answer and always ask the student to back up what they say. Your class is alive and your ability to control the discussions keeps the class in the direction needed for this lesson.
column57: In each class I have watched your students are engaged throughout the lesson. Your students enjoy your class and they retain much of the lessons taught as shown in their discussions and supporting their answers. The assessments you used were through your questions and discussions which the whole class took part in.
column59: This lesson was very well planned and executed. There was no differentiation shown in your lesson plan. Please include this in following lesson plans. You hit the points I look for in a lesson except for one but that may be due to the length of the video. This is where you have the students turn to one another and talk. You usually do have that in each lesson I have seen so I will write it off as not shown in video. I was very pleased to see your reflection as it was right on target. You are a very good teacher now and will continue only get better 

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79 Safari/537.36 Edge/14.14393
column49: Due to the individuation of the activity part of the lesson, differentiation was evident in how each student interpreted the activity. One student had a para to work with while the young lady who came in late engaged minimally in the class.
column53: The two boys in front enjoy the class as shown by their active engagement in all aspects of it. The girl who worked with the para seemed to have worked to her ability but was not comfortable reading out the response she worked on. I would read her response out to the class (or have the para) until she is more confident. The girl who came in late got to work when she came in but got distracted with her cell phone.  The class knows what is expected and gets right down to work. There was no confusion due to the classroom procedures that have been put in place. The only misbehavior was the girl with the phone. Ms. Burden did direct her to put her phone away but she was completely ignored. Ms. Burden could have been stronger in her direction but not too strong as to begin a power struggle. A behavior modification needs to be put in place to help both student and teacher.
column57: Three students were engaged throughout the lesson while one (girl with phone) was engaged about 65%. This was a better than usual class for her. The first year of teaching is the most difficult year as we figure out how to structure each lesson and engage our students. More activities are needed and less teacher centered classes. In your lesson plan you gave two assessments, neither of which were shown in class. I would also suggest with the first assessment (thumbs up or down for the Do Now Check) that you around the room and reviewed the response to the Do Now to get a clearer idea if the students with the thumbs up actually understood the question or they didn't want to look "dumb" in their classmate's eyes by putting their thumbs down. There was no time for an exit slip which means the lesson is too long and needs to be shorten to fit this shorter (Wednesday) period.
column59: Each lesson must have a Do Now, Stop and Jot, Turn and Talk and Exit Slip. You had 2 of the 4 in the lesson and while you had Turn and Talk in your lesson plan it was not evidenced in class. I would like to see all 4 my next visit.  Some suggestions to help you 	Find the best Global teacher at your school and arrange to visit a few times. 	Go to the NYCDOE Employees, teacher page (schools.nyc.gov) Then find the box that offers New Teacher Support. The first two links will be extremely helpful for you. The first link will lead you to Edutopia's tool kit for new teachers and the second will take you to WeTeach NYC where you can search for lesson and professional learning resources.  	I also suggest Khanacademy.org to look for help Your lesson plan was good but you need to find ways to bring it to life and get the class excited and you must show how you are differentiating your lesson. You have a wonderful relationship with your students that shows they trust you and you care about them. This is the number one key in the making of a good teacher. I look forward to continuing our work together

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/51.0.2704.79 Safari/537.36 Edge/14.14393
column49: By holding and reading from your lesson plan, I felt you were not yet comfortable with the material. Think of teaching like acting where you are learning a new script every day. Find a way to memorize the key points and the rest will follow. The questions you answered for this assignment were asking of YOUR knowledge of content and pedagogy, not the classes.
column53: All behavior was good so there was no need manage anything
column57: Your questions were much better which lead to students giving longer answers. Unfortunately, I could not hear the responses. I was pleased to see all students were engaged in this lesson. They got up without prompting and moved around the room to the different pictures with the time allowed for each one. I would have like to have seen the follow up of this activity and the writing the students did but that is not a part of a snap shot of a class.  I liked this lesson and as I said in my response to engaging students in learning, I wished I had the opportunity to see the full lesson. As you moved around the room you were assessing the students and the work they did. In your written response you said Not Applicable. There must be assessment threaded throughout every lesson taught.
column59: I gave you a 1 for reflecting on teaching due to your responses in the written part of this assignment. At our next meeting (February 15th) I want to review the questions you were to answer so you have a clear idea of what was asked and will be able to respond correctly the next time.

column49: I believe you know what you want to your students to know but are having trouble figuring out how to get them there. Your lessons are planned and I can see the steps you want to lead the class through but the most important part is missing. That is the students understanding and retaining the information. The is much too much information in each lesson. You may feel good about keeping up with curriculum but if the students can't take the information with them it doesn't do them any good. I sent you some links that might help you to broaden your lesson or give you some ideas.
column53: I need to see excitement in the lesson. This comes from you as the deliverer of the instruction. It's very hard exciting a class of 2 or 3 students, but if it doesn't start with the teacher the students will not be able to pump any life into the class. Your class likes you and will do whatever you ask them to do. If you accept a bare minimum, that is all they will give. The more you ask of them, the more they will give. This is an area of strength. You are very good at setting up and managing the classroom procedures from beginning to end which leads to no wasted time.  Absolutely no behavior problems are exhibited in your class.
column57: There was very little interaction between you and the students. In reviewing the Do Now, they discussed their answers and you were very encouraging in getting them to give full sentences but there needs to be a lot more interaction in the class. As we discussed many of your worksheets do not allow the students to think on their own. There is a lot of filling in the blanks which I understand is a good way for the class to get notes, but they can't seem to get past the coping of text when they need to answer questions in their own words. I would like to see discussion between the students and talk of the text read. I loved your annotated notes summary sheet that was on the smart board as the students were (silently) reading the text. This could have been used as an assessment if you reviewed what they annotated on their pages. Was there words they didn't know? What where the important themes discussed? What did they think they needed to know? These are some good questions that I would have liked to have known the answers too.  We not only need to have assessment threaded throughout the lesson, but the student need to be told how they are doing. I didn't see enough of this.
column59: I need to get more specific examples on how you would change your lesson to make it more effective. Not being able to find enough information on a topic is not enough. You have to start thinking outside of the box… what else can you do to add to your lesson. Tap into your creativity and come up with some ideas that will add to your lessons.

column49: Your lesson began with a Do Now where the class needed to look at a picture and respond with a See, Think and Wonder. This same picture was used later in the lesson where the class got to reflect on their response vs the meaning of the picture. Your objectives for the class 	Connect the black death with the Bubonic Plague as one in the same disease  	The steps in how it was transmitted and spread 	The connection between the Do Now and the lesson 	Negative affect of the Bubonic Plagued   	Benefits derived from the Bubonic Plague Your handouts are thoughtfully done which you put together by using the instructional content mandated for this 9th grade Global class. The modifications give the students just the right amount of information that they can retain and build upon in the next lesson.
column53: By teaching bell to bell and keeping your class at an excellent pace, the students are encouraged and motivated to learn. Your enthusiasm in teaching transfers to the students wanting to learn.  Vincent has been a difficult student each time I have visited your class. He talks out, often says things for shock value and uses inappropriate language. Each time Vincent acted out, you put him in check. Today after a few attempts, with each time escalating to the next step you would take, you had to have a private word with him outside your door. Vincent is a bright young man but this setting is not the correct one for him which I have mentioned to you. For Vincent's sake, I hope he is properly re-evaluated and placed in a more appropriate place.  Joshua had his head on his desk and did not respond to me coming over to him but I felt something was up with him as every other time he has been involved with the class. By the end of the class you were able to pull him into the lesson which I attribute to your ability to be in tune with each student in your class. During our meeting you shared with me Joshua was about to fight with Steve prior to your class. I wouldn't have known this as Steve was extremely involved in your lesson and amazing in class. This again I credit to your ability to have the students leave their problems at the door and enter into the lesson. Well done!!!
column57: Your questioning techniques are excellent and often lead from one student answering to another picking up on that answer and offering more. You always have good discussions going on in your class. Today Vincent answered a question with something that could have been inappropriate but you put a spin on it by changing the wording to make it work in the lesson. Your students feel safe and valued which gives them the confidence to engage in discussion. You have a very good sense of who your students are and how to pull them in or pull back when necessary. This was evident in how you worked with Joshua today. At just the right time you noticed when he was able to let go of what was bothering him and got him to answer a question involving him in the discussion.  You are constantly assessing your class both in their written work whic
column59: You felt you held the hands of the students by how you structured the lesson. I beg to differ. A well-structured lesson gives the class the ability to learn, provide discussions and reign them in when necessary. This is exactly what I observed today.

column49: Your 6th period self-contained class is reading Tim O'Brien's The Things They Carried. Unfortunately there are only two students in this class who are often there on different days. One student was working on one part of the lesson while another was working on a different section. You were working with both students on the parts of the lesson they were one. This gave the class the feeling of a setts class rather than a self-contained class.
column53: The two young men didn't particularly want to be there but once they were in the class, they did their work. Even though there were only two students they both presented behaviors that needed to be put in check which you did. With only two students you should not be seeing these behaviors. You need to set limits and expectations. Students cannot walk in and out of class as they please. Have a late book set up that must be signed by any student that walks in after the late bell. If a student goes to the bathroom, they should sign out and MUST take a bathroom pass with them. Some of the behaviors you are seeing in this class are seen in a larger scale in your elective English class.
column57: Your questions need to be broader which will help the class in forming better responses. Your questions encourage one word answers. To help encourage the student to give more than one word answers encourage the students to give you more instead of feeding them the answers. Once you settled the boys down, they did their work. The material you provided to the class breaks the lesson into bite size pieces which helps assess where the student is in the learning process.
column59: You were pleased with how Jermain was on task. He showed he had read the section of the book and he was able to answer the questions. For Edwin you would have him go back and pick out examples to give his answers more validity.

column49: Sharon is quite capable of presenting a well planned lesson to her students.  However I noticed some gaps in the lesson planning with this particular lesson.  Recipes and newspapers were provided for students to 'shop' for food on a budget.  However, the items listed on some of the recipes were not readily available to purchase with the newspapers at hand.  Perhaps estimates whould have been provided for students,  who had little shopping experience firsthand.  There seemed to be some confusion for students as how to proceed when the items they were looking for did not exist in the flyers provided.
column53: Students are generally well behaved in Sharon's classroom,  with only an occasional behavioral issue.  She handles them well,  with high expectations for good behavior.s
column57: In this particular lesson, all students were engaged in the learning process. They seemed to understand the assigned project well,  but stumbled when trying to figure out the independent work.  I have not noticed this with Sharon's classes before,  but this was a fairly intricate process which needed to be clarified.

column49: Georgina is a competent teacher.  However,  this particular class observed is extremely difficult to control.  Their interest is virtually nil, and they are all set to fail in their second marking period.  During the period I observed,  students were put on notice and some participated.  The lesson's objective was not difficult, and Georgina guided them through it,  leading them to draw conclusions from the material presented.  But when asked to refer to previous instruction,  most students could not respond. Georgina patiently led them through the lesson in order to achieve a satisfactory explanation of material presented.
column53: Georgina has set up standards of conduct which she expects all students to abide by.  However,  the school itself has little imposed structure, and this particular class is very difficult to work with,  even though high expectations are set by our Fellows.
column57: Georgina attempts to lead her students with higher order questioning.  She leads them effectively, in this particular lesson by referring them to photos discussed previously. All students are expected to participate.  Georgina's assessments place more responsibility on the student.  They are expected to work for a passing grade and be responsible for assignments missed.
column59: Georgina's reflection has led her to conducting a more structured classroom.  I believe that she accurately implements the structure these students need in order to succeed.

column49: In general,  Fiorella is assigned to teach Earth Science. We are working on adding creative and interesting presentations in order for students to recall material from previous lessons and make inferences about new material presented.
column53: In general,  Fiorella's students' behavior has improved.  However, much of the time is spent with one or two students distracting the class with poor behavior.  This has become commonplace.  We are working on making students accountable for good behavior as well as their studies.
column57: Fiorella states that she tests students every two weeks.  Her lessons consist mostly of a quick review of previous material,  a small amount of new material,  and a writing/copying of charts presented. In general,  behavior has markedly improved with this class, so perhaps Fiorella can move on more creatively.

column49: 1a) Ms. Maynard displays solid knowledge of the important concepts in the discipline and how these relate to one another. She demonstrates accurate understanding of prerequisite relationships among topics. Ms. Maynard's plans and practice reflect familiarity with a wide range of effective pedagogical approaches in the subject.  Ms. Maynard collaboratively planned this lesson with a colleague who has strong content knowledge. 1c) Most outcomes represent rigorous and important learning in the discipline and are clear, are written in the form of student learning, and suggest viable methods of assessment. Outcomes reflect several different types of learning and opportunities for coordination, and they are differentiated, in whatever way is needed, for different groups of students.  Ms. Maynard's plans include student choice which required students to increase their independence. 1d) Most of the learning activities are aligned with the instructional outcomes and follow an organized progression suitable to groups of students. The learning activities have reasonable time allocations; they represent significant cognitive challenge, with some differentiation for different groups of students and varied use of instructional groups. By incorporating the video component Ms. Maynard provided support access to the lesson's objectives.
column53: 2b)) Student behavior is generally appropriate. Ms. Maynard monitors student behavior against established standards of conduct. Her response to student misbehavior is consistent, proportionate, and respectful to students and is effective.  Ms. Maynard uses verbal and non-verbal cues, such as background music, to signal transitions during the lesson.   2c) There is little loss of instructional time due to effective classroom routines and procedures. column57: 3b) While the Ms. Maynard may use some low-level questions, she poses questions designed to promote student thinking and understanding. She challenges students to justify their thinking and successfully engages most students in the discussion, employing a range of strategies to ensure that most students are heard.     3c) The learning tasks and activities are fully aligned with the instructional outcomes and are designed to challenge student thinking, inviting students to make their thinking visible. This technique results in active intellectual engagement by most students with important and challenging content, and with teacher scaffolding to support that engagement. column49: 1a) Ms. Locust displays solid knowledge of the important concepts in the discipline and how these relate to one another. column53: 2b) Ms. Locust has created a classroom culture where learning is valued by all; high expectations for both learning and hard work are the norm for most students. column57: 3b) While Ms. Locust may use some low-level questions, she poses questions designed to promote student thinking and understanding. column49: Joy is progressing nicely in the area of instructional planning.  We are working on the structure of her lessons as well as student understanding of the need for structure in their work. column57: Joy accepts all answers from her students without provoking discussion or questions from other students. column59: Joy seems pleased with her lessons in general because she attempts to employ some creative activities within the lesson.  Again we are working on structuring a lesson within a workshop model.

column49: This was not a usual lesson for you with the outcomes very different than what I have seen in your class. It was clearly a review lesson yet right from the start you threw the class off with the Do Now. By asking them to match up 14 items using lines to connect the word with the correct response you put your class in freak out mode. From that point on, the class seemed a step off and never got back on track. There was no differentiation for different students.
column53: The classroom culture is a very busy place with learning valued by teacher and students. You very thoughtfully matched students so students could benefit from each other. Your response to misbehavior is consistent and respectful to students
column57: The classroom culture is a very busy place with learning valued by teacher and students. You very thoughtfully matched students so students could benefit from each other. This helps keeps things going in your class with no loss of instructional time. Today's class was more out of sorts than usual but there were no behavior problems that needed to be addressed. Your response to misbehavior is consistent and respectful to students This may well be due to the type of lesson but many of your questions led students through a single path of inquiry with answers seemingly determined in advance.  The students did not seem to be moving together when you went over the multiple choose. Many were not able to hear what was going on as they were distracted by wanting to have the correct answer without wanting to know why the answer was correct. The class at one point asked you to slow down as you seemed to be going to fast for them. They were all working, but I wondered if they were all learning or just going through the motions. The whole lesson was an assessment since it was a review.
column59: During our review you accurately assessed your lesson and what needs to be done to make it much more effective. As always, I look forward to my next visit with you.

column49: The do now was an excellent start to your class. The topic was one everyone could relate to and write about. You got almost 100% participation  You seem more confident in what you are doing with this class and they in turn are available to do the work required of them.
column53: 2b. Establishing a culture for learning = 4 During the reading you were highlighting the text and used an overhead projector that picked up the text and put it on your smart board. This helped some students but I felt your class needed your physical presence by walking around the class more. Suggestion-have a student sit at your desk and read the text (silently) while moving the (already marked) pages as needed.  2c. Managing classroom procedures = 3 As the class began you were at the door with the student's folders, notebooks and the lesson for the day to hand out to the class. You need to have a late book handy for those that come in late. It takes your class a good 10 minutes to come in and settle down. I suggest you project a clock on your smart board so the class can see how much time to complete their activities. You gave out stickers to students on task throughout the lesson which motivated students to stay on task. 2d. Managing student behavior = 3 One young man came to class late and instead of him going straight to his seat and begin working he walked around offering his candy to others. You just continued your lesson as this was going on. Later you began to walk around the room and stand next to this same student which was a big help in keeping his behavior on track and focused. When one student was sharing, class was not respectful which you pointed out to class.          I was very pleased to see this class much more on track than in my past visits though I still think you need to make sure the 3 students in the back are never paired up together.
column57: 3b. Using questioning / prompts and discussion = 4  You engaged the full class during this lesson. A lot of work was done in groups which they then shared out with the class. The questions in the Think section of their worksheet were good questions to get them writing but there could have been more discussion about the reading before they began the writing. 3c. Engaging students in learning = 4 You began the class with an excellent Do Now that the class got the opportunity to share out. This was a very good way to start the class and it led right into the lesson. If you can minimize the time wasted on the students entering the class and beginning their Do Now, you will have more time to complete your lesson. Your exit slip (which you were not able to get to) contained a self-checklist that had scaffolding to support the students engagement. 3d. Using assessment in instruction = 4 There was assessment evident throughout the lesson in the form of student writing and your verbal reaction to their writing. You moved around the room, met with and talk to everyone in the class.
column59: You reflected on what you could have done differently in your class to make it an even better lesson.  This helped you make an accurate assessment of the lesson's effectiveness and the extent to which it achieved its instructional outcomes. This was a much stronger lesson that I have seen in the past and I look forward to continuing to watch you grow as a teacher.

column49: You need to be more than a lesson beyond the students. With a deeper knowledge of the information you will be able to give the students a richer experience which will promote learning and retention. Trust that your students are capable of learning at a higher level. If you raise the bar, the class will follow.
column53: 2b. Establishing a culture for learning = 3 More rigor is needed. If you reach high you will get so much more from the class. Always expect more and you will get more. You have a class available to learn, give them the opportunity to explore what they are capable of doing. 2c. Managing classroom procedures = 4 This is a strong point for you and your class runs efficiently due to your classroom procedures are set and students are aware of the expectations of your class. 2d. Managing student behavior = n/a Your class engages without any behavior issues each and every time I have visited.
column57: 3b. Using questioning / prompts and discussion = 2 You need to led the class into discussions. Each student is a valuable member of each discussion and has things to offer. By working discussions into the class the class will learn how to be an active participant who can learn from each member of the group. Try having them turn their chairs so they can see and talk to each other. Spend a little time going over some of the videos in Engageny.org/video-library.  I filtered my search by HS/Commencement level. Look at (teacher provides feedback to students and teacher engages students in discussion) which are part of Danielson Domain 3 that deal with instruction and the different components of instruction.  3c. Engaging students in learning = 3 Here is a definition of engagement. Within your class each student falls to some degree along this line of thought with one student on one end and another at the opposite. Felipe captures most of what is written to a high degree while the young lady shows a minimal amount of enthusiasm. The goal is to try and minimize the gap between the engaged student and the one just going through the motion with the hope of engaging all students to the degree of the most engaged. The degree of attention, curiosity, interest, optimism, and passion kids show or display when they are learning or being taught, which extends to the level of motivation they have to learn and progress in their education. 3d. Using assessment in instruction = 2 I am not seeing much assessment in your lessons. You return work to the students but do not give verbal feedback to them on the work done both written (the returned work) or verbal (work in class). Students need to get this feedback so the know what is going on. They also need to be aware of the assessment criteria used to evaluate their work. Please watch a few of the videos I recommended on student engagement and assessment that shows how a teacher both engages and assesses their class.
column59: Your lessons have been improving but not to the degree needed to see a great change. You have a lot of good things in place (classroom routines, students available to learn, your organization) but as discussed until you know more about the subject you will have a hard time getting the students to dig deeper into the lesson. Take advantage of teachable moments which constantly come up in your class. This will give your class the richness it needs and deserves.

column49: I visited a CTT/ICT setting where you were not the lead teacher which made it more difficult for me to see you teaching. Your job in the lesson plan as the Special Ed teacher was to modify and differentiate the lesson which you did quite well.
column53: 2b. Establishing a culture for learning = 4 There was a lot going on in this class in terms of behavior and student ability and as you went from table to table you worked with all the students, not just the special ed ones. This makes for a better class environment. The class was grouped heterogeneously which worked well in this class. Is was not apparent which students were special ed and as you moved around you worked with all the students.  2c. Managing classroom procedures = 5 Today was the first day a new plan was rolled out for giving out calculators. The plan called for each table to have a group leader who was responsible for collecting ID's from the group to exchange for borrowing a calculator. This new plan was explained well and the class easily complied. All classroom procedures were know to the class with help run this class to the best of it's ability. 2d. Managing student behavior = 3 This is one area that was a problem in today's class. Students walked in and out of class without a pass and at one point 3 students left together. No one signed a late log (3 came in late) nor signed a bathroom log.  In the beginning of class I noticed 3 students with ear buds in their ears, the number increased as the class went on. 2 Students wore hats, 1 was eating and multiple cell phones were out and being used for texting. 2 times the lead teacher was working with a group while one student in the group was texting and nothing was said. This was right after she announced anyone with a phone out was getting a call home. I felt the students didn't believe there were any consequences to their behaviors so they did what they wanted as long as they got their work done.
column57: 3b. Using questioning / prompts and discussion = 4 Your job was to modify the lesson and make sure the students were doing what they needed to do. Since you were not leading the class this question can be directed to when you were working with the groups. Each time I saw you working with a group, the group was engaged and working to solve the problems together. 3c. Engaging students in learning = 5 By moving around and working with the students and challenging the ones that were moving faster, you kept the students engaged. 3d. Using assessment in instruction = 5 You were responsible for checking the students' performance which included work completed as well as those that were not following the rules of the class. This is a very important part of assessing the behaviors and work of each student.
column59: In our discussion you had many things to say about how you would handle the class in a do over. I felt you worked very well with the lead teacher with the exception on the behavior situation. Neither one of you wanted to be the enforcer but one of you (or better both of you) need to be. Even if it's the culture of the school for kids to do what they want, it doesn't have to be the culture of your class. You were right on target with what you shared you would do given the chance to teach this class again and I look forward to coming to your class and seeing your growth each and every time.

column49: At the onset of the lesson students were asked to explain what is meant by author's style. The teacher linke the topic of authors style to other readings ad students were to make onnections. Techniques related to author's style were also discussed such as mood, tone, etc. Some content was also presented though a video. The tasks and directions were clear. Further clarity was provided through the video. Th lesson was seqentially developed and was challenging for students.
column53: The classroom climate/culture is supportive of learning. Students offered responses to questions and were attuned to the topic. The students behavior was appropriate. Transitions from different points of the lesson were smooth. There was evidence that routines have been established, and evidence of classroom expectation were present. Instructional time was appropriate. The teacher redirected one or two students when necessary. However, in most instances there was not a need to redirect students as they were on task and involved in the lesson content. The teacher has exercises more of a role in addressing behavior when needed.
column57: Questions wer presented in a manner to promote thinking and allowed students to offer explanations for their responses. Students were assessed through discussing questions and making connections regardin authors style to the current reading as well as connections to style in other readings from prior materials. Assessment was also evident as they answered questions on other elements as word choice, dialogue, tone, mood etc.  The impact of words was also discussed as related to authors style.
column59: She indicated she could have further assessed students through writing assignments/questions connected to the passage. Also, for students that are having more difficulty break up the material into smaller segments. She also noted that she should have had students summarize/ or use an exit ticket prior to ending the lesson.

column53: The only thing that could be improved from this lesson is that the Teaching Fellow finished the lesson with five minutes extra time. We discussed what she needs to do in case she ends a lesson too soon.
column57: All procedures ran smoothly, every student was engaged in learning, and the Teaching Fellow asked relevant and thought provoking lessons. She assessed throughout the lesson.
column59: I see a significant improvement with this Teaching Fellow. She has the academic and social/emotional well being of her students as a priority.

column49: Adriana displays knowledge of important concepts in the discipline of Global History. She is well prepared and learning activities are aligned with instructional outcomes. The learning activities are cognitively challenging and there was evidence of differentiation for different groups of students.
column53: Adriana and her co-teacher have established classroom routines and procedures. The implementation is consistent and student behavior is appropriate.
column57: On 3/16, students were working in groups of 3 and engaged in a research project with a focus of the causes of WWI. The students were engaged in learning and their research. Adriana used questioning techniques when working in small groups to help foster discussion and dialogue regarding their topic.

column49: This was a difficult Math lesson on finding the areas of parallelograms, rhombuses, and trapezoids. column53: As previously stated, there were no behavior issues, and her students were eager to learn. However, the Teaching Fellow told me that it will take multiple lessons for mastery.

column49: The lesson focused on analyzing key details. Class discussion focused on what they need to know in order to idetify key details. Discussion of the ability to make sense of the meaning of words within sentences and paragraphs enable us to analyze key details. Key details were discussed as students were presented with a video to view. A chart was set up in order to enable students o respond to questions. The teacher modeled how the material should be set up in order to address the question. Students were given a model of how the chart was to be set up in order to affirm or refute a comment. Details had to suuport their refuting or affirming a statement based on what was viewed in the video. The subject matter was taught through use of a video which served to connect with the vsual learner, and auditory learner.  The chart also served to enable students to organize their thoughts.
column53: Students were engaged in the learning process. Students were actively engaged in clarifying the work that needed to be addressed in order to complete the task. The classroom culture provided opportunities for student to work with their classmates to ensure that they were on target at some points during the lesson. Classroom procedures appear to be in place. Transitions from questioning, video viewing and discussion were appropriate. Time element was appropriate, along with student behavior. There were not any behavior issues.
column57: Students were assessed through varied questioning. Pupils provided key details as they responded to questions. The techer provided feedback to students, and students provided responses to questions involving the actions of the character and the key details supporting statements. Furher assessment of students should be incoported by students completing the chart as they frame their answers noting key details to support statements.
column59: The teacher noted that less time initially could have been spent on the Do Now activity. For students that require more support a chart could be adapted to further guide them in order to specify key details from the material presented.

column49: She provided a lesson plan noting the learning objectives. However, the lesson observed only addressed some of the learning objectives at the onset of the lesson. Some basic characteristics of landscapes were reviewed with the class. Pictures were viewed to enable students to review prior lesson topics. Therewas brief reading of a paragraph wa preseted to th class. The passage was read loud before students had to work into groups andcomplet the task of coloring various landscape regions in N.Y. The majority of the period was spent as pupils engaged in this activity. The lesson objective- Explain the effect of climate on landscape development was not dicusse at all.
column53: Students were given opportunities to review basic information regarding landscapes from a prior lesson. New information was not imparted to students. There was no discussion regarding the effect of climate on landscape development. The short passage on landscapes was presented with limited questioning. Classroom procedures are in place. However, instructional time was not maximized due to the fact that a great deal of time was spent on one activity which impacted the learning process.The students behavior was appropriate during the period observed and there were no behavior issues exhibited.
column57: The teacher posed a limited amount of questions to students throughout the lesson. When questions were posed they were basic and did not reflect higher order thinking. Questions reflected non-challenging and/or thought provoking. Tasks were limited and the majority of the lesson involved students coloring in land regions and landscapes from the map presented. There was limited egagement in discussion of the topic, and there was no mention of explaining the effect of climate on landscape development that was a noted objective in the lesson plan. The pacing of the lesson was not in alignment in order to enable students to address the learning objectve as stated. Too much time was spent on having students color in land regions. Lesson needs to be challenging and various opportunities to engage in discussion and assess learning.
column59: The teacher noted that questioning and discussion that enable students to think and delve deeper need to be evident in her lessons. She also acknowledged that the duration of the activity lasted too long.

column49: This U.S. History lesson had excellent possibilities. It was presented as a " Flash Debate" with this theme: " Should the Founding Fathers have signed the Constitution?" Students were to take sides ( Federalists/AntiFederalists. However, this is a Transfer School, and most of the Teaching Fellow's students are low credited because of previous Truancy issues. That said, the Fellow knew that prior knowledge would be weak, but he was not able to connect real world relevance and personal relevance. He will break down this material and deliver it so that his students can relate.
column53: The procedures were fine, and his students were well behaved. They were ready to learn, but they had a hard time making the connecctions between the Constitution and their lives.
column57: The Teaching Fellow tried asking thought provoking question, but the lack of student prior knowledge hindered responses.
column59: The Teaching Fellow will get to work on making lessons relevant to his students' real world and their lives.

column49: This was a Science lesson entitled, " How do rocks change." column53: The Teaching Fellow's students were extremely well behaved ( three Paraprofessionals in the room), her procedures were fine, and she assessed throughout the lesson.
column57: This group of students had many profound academic deficiences, but the Teaching Fellow did her best to compensate.
column59: This is a Teaching Fellow who is progressing. She does care about her students well being.
